al Mediation -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScholars have extensively documented the historical and socioeconomic impact of the Dutch East India Company. They have paid much less attention to the company’s significant influence on Asian art and visual culture. Mediating Netherlandish Art and Material Culture in Asia addresses this imbalance with a wide range of contributions covering such topics as Dutch and Chinese art in colonial and indigenous households; the rise of Hollandmania in Japan; and the Dutch painters who worked at the court of the Persian shahs. Together, the contributors shed new light on seventeenth-century Dutch visual culture—and the company that spread it across Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArt, AsianxEuropean influences. 0aArt, NetherlandishxAsian influences. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBok, Marten Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakravarti, Ranabir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErll, Astrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrer, Matthi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufmann, Thomas DaCosta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufmann, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKobayashi-Sato, Yoriko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrieger, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandau, Amy S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNas, Peter J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https:/